<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-454-856  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 454 856.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 24 1989 v23 n30 p33(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fed red tape blunts PC cutting edge. (slowness of governmentprocurement process results in acquiring obsolete technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Barney, Douglas.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The federal government is rapidly deploying microcomputers toincrease worker efficiency in many of its agencies, but criticscharge that the bureaucratic procurement process can result in theacquisition of obsolete technology.andP;  Specifications which do nottake recent technical advances into account often lead to thepurchase of out-of-date equipment that is not fully supported oroptimized.andP;  Government agencies also have difficulty attractingthe talent necessary to take advantage of leading-edge technologybecause their pay scales lag behind those of private industry.andO;Contracting work out to independents leads to problems with lackof control, instability of both the contractor and the agency, andhigher costs.andP;  A few procurement contracts, such as the SocialSecurity Administration's plan for 80386-based computers, do keepup with the state of the art.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersObsolescenceGovernment ContractsSystem SelectionBureaucracy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>